cularName":"Giant Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Freckled Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Burrfish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Black-spotted Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Ballonfish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Ajargo","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Spotfin porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Baiacu-de-espinho","language":"por"},{"vernacularName":"Djiendja"},{"vernacularName":"Djindja"},{"vernacularName":"Hedgehog","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"Spot-fin Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"puerco espín","language":"spa"},{"vernacularName":"porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"pez erizo pecoso","language":"spa"},{"vernacularName":"Porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"pez erizo pecoso","language":"spa"},{"vernacularName":"ネズミフグ","language":"jpn"},{"vernacularName":"spot-fin porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"porcupinefish","language":"eng"},{"vernacularName":"ネズミフグ","language":"jpn"},{"vernacularName":"Nezumifugu","language":"jpn"}],"synonym":false,"higherClassificationMap":{"1":"Animalia","44":"Chordata","772":"Tetraodontiformes","5898":"Diodontidae","2406531":"Diodon"}},{"key":191883199,"datasetKey":"75ffcff3-6336-4f6a-8d0b-94c082519099","nubKey":5213374,"parentKey":324306003,"parent":"Diodon","kingdom":"Animalia","phylum":"Chordata","order":"Tetraodontiformes","family":"Diodontidae","genus":"Diodon","species":"Diodon hystrix","kingdomKey":324305526,"phylumKey":324305527,"classKey":324305677,"orderKey":324306000,"familyKey":324306001,"genusKey":324306003,"speciesKey":191883199,"scientificName":"Diodon hystrix Linnaeus 1758","canonicalName":"Diodon hystrix","authorship":"Linnaeus 1758","nameType":"SCIENTIFIC","taxonomicStatus":"ACCEPTED","rank":"SPECIES","origin":"SOURCE","numDescendants":0,"numOccurrences":0,"taxonID":"03BE87D6FF70FF5498EAFAC8FB73362B.taxon","habitats":[],"nomenclaturalStatus":[],"threatStatuses":[],"descriptions":[{"description":"Freckled Porcupinefish, Porcupinefish, Spotfin Porcupinefish, or Spotted Porcupinefish. To 91 cm (36 in) TL (Miller and Lea 1972). Circumglobal; western Pacific Ocean north to Japan (Aizawa in Nakabo 2002) and southeast of Kuril Islands (Parin 2003); Santa Barbara (34 ° 24 ’ N, 119 ° 45 ’ W), southern California (Personal communication: Santa Barbara Natural History Museum Fish Collection, Santa Barbara, California) to Chile, including Gulf of California and Islas Galápagos (Miller and Lea 1972). Benthic; depth: surface (nightlight: 52 - 415), intertidal to 135 m (443 ft) (min.: Arndt and Fricke 2019; max.: Ralston et al. 1986)."}],"vernacularNames":[],"synonym":false,"higherClassificationMap":{"324305526":"Animalia","324305527":"Chordata","324305677":"Actinopterygii","324306000":"Tetraodontiformes","324306001":"Diodontidae","324306003":"Diodon"},"class":"Actinopterygii"},{"key":165787468,"datasetKey":"cbb6498e-8927-405a-916b-576d00a6289b","species":"Chilomycterus reticulatus","speciesKey":165787468,"scientificName":"Chilomycterus reticulatus (Linnaeus, 1758)","canonicalName":"Chilomycterus reticulatus","authorship":"(Linnaeus, 1758)","nameType":"SCIENTIFIC","taxonomicStatus":"ACCEPTED","rank":"SPECIES","origin":"SOURCE","numDescendants":0,"numOccurrences":0,"taxonID":"37677563","habitats":[],"nomenclaturalStatus":[],"threatStatuses":[],"descriptions":[{"description":"The spotfin burrfish (Chilomycterus reticulatus), also called the spotted burrfish, Pacific burrfish, spotfin porcupinefish or few-spined porcupinefish, is a species of fish in the genus Chilomycterus, which is part of the porcupinefish family Diodontidae."},{"description":"Chilomycterus reticulatus has a rotund body, which can be inflated, with a wide, blunt head and large eyes. The nasal organ of adults sits in an open, pitted cup which in juveniles is a tentacle with two openings. The teeth are fused into a parrot like beak with no frontal groove and the mouth is large. The fins lack spines and there are no pelvic fins, the dorsal fin has 12-14 rays, the anal fin has 11-14 rays, the caudal fin has 10 rays and there are 19-22 rays in the large pectoral fins. The body is covered in small spines which are triangular on cross section, some of which are reduced to plates under the skin. There is a row of 8-10 spines which runs from the head to the dorsal fin, and there are one or two spines on the caudal peduncle. Adult C. reticulatus are grey to brown in colour with a black gular band and small black spots on upper surfaces and fins. The pelagic juveniles are blue in colour with dark spots above, the spots reaching to the belly. They grow to a standard length of 50 cm but up to 75 cm has been recorded Chilomycterus reticulatus"},{"description":"Chilomycterus reticulatus is rather patchily distributed in warm temperate seas throughout the world in the Pacific, Atlantic, including the Gulf of Mexico and Mediterranean Sea, and Indian Oceans. In the Atlantic it reaches as far north as North Carolina in the west and Portugal in the east and south to South Africa and Brazil, in the Indo-Pacific it extends north to Japan and south to northern New Zealand and in the eastern Pacific it is found from Chile north to California."},{"description":"Chilomycterus reticulatus is found among coral and rocky reefs at depths down to 140m, but has also been caught in trawls over softer substrates. It is normally found at depths of less than 25m and it feeds mainly on hard shelled invertebrates, including molluscs, echinoderms and crustaceans. They eggs and larvae are pelagic, juveniles are often found among floating weed mats and become demersal at around 20 cm. The adults are active by day and at night they sleep braced against the substrate. They are frequently encountered washed up on beaches."}],"vernacularNames":[],"synonym":false,"higherClassificationMap":{}}],"facets":[]}